        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Thread.Suspend, Garbage Collection, and Safe Points</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>When you call <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.Suspend%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> on a thread, the system notes that a thread suspension has been requested and allows the thread to execute until it has reached a safe point before actually suspending the thread.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A safe point for a thread is a point in its execution at which garbage collection can be performed.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Once a safe point is reached, the runtime guarantees that the suspended thread will not make any further progress in managed code.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A thread executing outside managed code is always safe for garbage collection, and its execution continues until it attempts to resume execution of managed code.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>In order to perform a garbage collection, the runtime must suspend all the threads except the thread performing the collection.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Each thread must be brought to a safe point before it can be suspended.</source>
        </trans-unit>
